RFC 9111 Section 4.3.5:
When a cache makes an inbound HEAD request for a target URI and receives a 200 (OK) response,
the cache SHOULD update or invalidate each of its stored GET responses
that could have been chosen for that request [...]

-- cache.txt --
GET http://www.example.com/foo HTTP/1.1
Date: Sat, 01 Jan 2000 00:00:00 GMT

HTTP/1.1 200 OK
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=utf-8
Content-Length: 15
Cache-Control: max-age=0
ETag: "xyzzy"
Date: Sat, 01 Jan 2000 00:00:00 GMT

Hello, World!
HEAD http://www.example.com/foo HTTP/1.1
Date: Sat, 01 Jan 2000 00:00:05 GMT

HTTP/1.1 200 OK
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=utf-8
Content-Length: 15
Cache-Control: max-age=604800
ETag: "xyzzy"
Date: Sat, 01 Jan 2000 00:00:05 GMT

GET http://www.example.com/foo HTTP/1.1
Date: Sat, 01 Jan 2000 00:00:10 GMT

HTTP/1.1 200 OK
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=utf-8
Content-Length: 15
Cache-Control: max-age=604800
ETag: "xyzzy"
Date: Sat, 01 Jan 2000 00:00:05 GMT
Age: 5

Hello, World!
-- server.txt --
GET http://www.example.com/foo HTTP/1.1
Host: www.example.com
Date: Sat, 01 Jan 2000 00:00:00 GMT

HTTP/1.1 200 OK
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=utf-8
Content-Length: 15
Cache-Control: max-age=0
ETag: "xyzzy"
Date: Sat, 01 Jan 2000 00:00:00 GMT

Hello, World!
HEAD http://www.example.com/foo HTTP/1.1
Host: www.example.com
Date: Sat, 01 Jan 2000 00:00:05 GMT

HTTP/1.1 200 OK
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=utf-8
Content-Length: 15
Cache-Control: max-age=604800
ETag: "xyzzy"
Date: Sat, 01 Jan 2000 00:00:05 GMT

